commit.message: Update snapshot for React 18

Update rendering the react app

Adjust rendering the root component for React 18.
See https://react.dev/blog/2022/03/08/react-18-upgrade-guide#updates-to-client-rendering-apis
for more details.

Change: Update to React 18

Update to the latest React version

Fix: Remove warning when running lint staged pre-commit hook

Running `git add` is obsolete with the lint-staged version in use.

Fix "Error: Not implemented: navigation (except hash changes)" during tests

JSDOM doesn't implement the navigation API and therefore raises an error
in the console if `window.location` is used and anchors are clicked. As
we are using a lot of anchors in our pages this error is raised often
during test runs. By mocking the HTMLAnchorElement click handler the
console error is silenced.

Update copyright in footer and about page

We are in 2024 already.

Change: Update link to GMP to 22.5 version

Also update the link component to use hooks instead of the withGmp HOC.

Change: Update datepicker to use current version of react-datepicker

react-datepicker > 1.8.0 dropped the usage of moment.js and requires
native JS Date objects as inputs. Therefore we didn't update it for a
long time. This change adjusts our own datepicker component to still use
moment.js dates and passes the wrapped JS Date objects to
react-datepicker. Because native Date objects don't know anything about
timezone the datepicker component requires a timezone prop now to be
able to convert the native Date object into a timezone aware moment.js
date.

This change might also fix a small issue with out datepicker component
on initial creation. The datepicker created a moment.js date having
possibly the wrong timezone information.

Also with updating react-datepicker to the latest release all blockers
for updating to React 18 are resolved.

commit.message:
Allow to rebuild a specific container image

Use workflow dispatch event to trigger a re-build of a specific
container image. Therefore the passed tag will be checked out. The git
tag and sha from the checkout will be used to determine the container
image labels instead of deriving them from the github workflow context.
